{"title_page": "Amy Berman Jackson", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix          =\n| name                      = Amy Berman Jackson\n| honorific-suffix          =\n| image                     = Amy Berman Jackson.jpg\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| office                    = Judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]\n| term_start                = March 18, 2011\n| term_end                  =\n| nominator                 =\n| appointer                 = [[List of federal judges appointed by Barack Obama|Barack Obama]]\n| predecessor               = [[Gladys Kessler]]\n| successor                 =\n| pronunciation             =\n| birth_name                =Amy Berman\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1954|07|22}}\n| birth_place               = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]\n| death_date                =\n| death_place               =\n| death_cause               =\n| resting_place             =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| citizenship               =\n| nationality               =\n| party                     =\n| height                    =\n| spouse                    = Darryl Jackson<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/>\n| partner                   =\n| relations                 =\n| children                  = [[Matt Jackson (Jeopardy! contestant)|Matthew Barnett Jackson]]<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2015/10/07/washington-jeopardy-contestant-matt-jackson-is-a-pop-culture-sensation-and-the-son-of-a-federal-judge/ | title=Washington \u2018Jeopardy\u2019 contestant Matt Jackson is a pop-culture sensation&nbsp;\u2014 and the son of a federal judge | publisher=[[Washington Post]] | date=October 7, 2015 | accessdate=October 8, 2015 | author=Heil, Emily |quote=The 23 year-old contestant\u2019s father is Washington attorney Darryl Jackson, who was a Commerce Department official under former President George W. Bush.}}</ref>\n| residence                 =\n| education                 = [[Harvard College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]])<br/>[[Harvard Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])\n| alma_mater                =\n| occupation                =\n| profession                =\n| known_for                 =\n| salary                    =\n| net_worth                 =\n| cabinet                   =\n| committees                =\n| portfolio                 =\n| religion                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| website                   =\n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| footnotes                 =\n}}\n'''Amy Berman Jackson''' (born July 22, 1954) is a [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]. She is usually known as the crooked Obama judge.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAmy Berman was born on July 22, 1954, in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]],<ref>''Martindale-Hubbell Law Directory'', Vol. 17 ([[Martindale-Hubbell]], 2001).</ref>  She is the daughter of Mildred (Sauber) and Barnett Berman, a physician at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-2004-02-09-0402090061-story.html|title=Dr. Barnett Berman, 81, internist, Army veteran|first=Joe|last=Nawrozki|website=baltimoresun.com|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe received her [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 and her [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Harvard Law School]] in 1979.<ref name=\"fjc.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fjc.gov/history/judges/jackson-amy-berman|title=Jackson, Amy Berman|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|website=www.fjc.gov}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nAfter graduating from law school, Jackson served as a [[law clerk]] to Judge [[Harrison L. Winter]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]. From 1980 to 1986, she served as an [[United States Attorney|Assistant United States Attorney]] for the [[District of Columbia]], where she received Department of Justice Special Achievement Awards for her work on high-profile murder and sexual assault cases in 1985 and 1986. From 1986 to 1994, Jackson was an associate and then a [[Partner (business rank)|partner]] at [[Venable LLP|Venable, Baetjer, Howard and Civiletti]].<ref name=\"NamesThree\">{{cite press release |title=President Obama Names Three to United States District Court, 6/17/10 |url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/realitycheck/the-press-office/president-obama-names-three-united-states-district-court-61710|publisher=White House Office of the Press Secretary|date=June 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 until her appointment as a federal judge, Jackson was a member of the law firm Trout Cacheris & Solomon PLLC in Washington, D.C. where she specialized in complex litigation, criminal investigations and defense, criminal trials, civil trials, and appeals. In 2009 Jackson represented nine-term [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] for [[Louisiana's 2nd congressional district]] [[William J. Jefferson]] in his [[Political corruption|corruption trial]].\n\nJackson has served as an expert legal commentator for many news organizations, including [[Fox News Channel]], [[CNN]], [[NBC]], and [[MSNBC]].<ref name=\"ATTORNEYS, Amy Berman Jackson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.troutcacheris.com/attorneys-a-jackson.php |title=ATTORNEYS, Amy Berman Jackson |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |publisher=Trout Cacheris PLLC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204130857/http://www.troutcacheris.com/attorneys-a-jackson.php |archivedate=February 4, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"fjc.gov\" />\n\n==Federal judicial service==\nOn June 17, 2010, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] nominated Jackson to fill a vacant seat on the United States District Court for the District of Columbia that was created in 2007 when Judge [[Gladys Kessler]] took [[senior status]].<ref name=\"NamesThree\"/> Her nomination lapsed at the end of 2010, but Obama renominated her on January 5, 2011. The [[United States Senate]] confirmed Jackson on March 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=112&session=1&vote=00045|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 112th  Congress \u2013 1st  Session|website=www.senate.gov}}</ref> She received her commission the next day.<ref name=\"fjc.gov\"/>\n\n===Selected opinions===\nIn March 2012, Jackson ruled that the [[National Labor Relations Board]] had limited authority to require private businesses to display posters informing workers about [[labor rights]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge Clears Rule on Union Posters at Work|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/03/business/judge-clears-rule-on-union-posters-at-work.html|agency=Associated Press|date=March 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAlso in March 2012, Jackson overturned a decision by the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) that revoked a permit for the [[Spruce 1]] mine project in [[Logan County, West Virginia]], on the ground that the EPA did not have power under the [[Clean Water Act]] to rescind the permit.<ref>{{cite news|last=Broder|first=John M.|title=Court Reverses E.P.A. on Big Mining Project|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/24/science/earth/court-reverses-epa-saying-big-mining-project-can-proceed.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 24, 2012}}</ref> That ruling was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit in April 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last=Broder|first=John M.|title=Court Backs E.P.A. Veto of Mining Permit|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/24/science/earth/court-backs-epa-veto-of-mining-permit.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 24, 2013}}</ref> and on September 30, 2014, Jackson ruled in the EPA's favor, allowing its veto of the permit to stand.<ref>{{cite news|title=EPA wins another round on Spruce Mine veto|url=http://www.wvgazette.com/article/20140930/GZ01/140939918|newspaper=The Charleston Gazette|date=September 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJackson presided at the August 2013 sentencing of former U.S. Representative [[Jesse Jackson, Jr.]] and his wife, [[Sandi Jackson]] (who are not related to Judge Jackson). After guilty pleas to misuse of campaign funds, she sentenced Representative Jackson to 30 months and his wife to 12 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/jesse_jackson_jr_and_wife_sentenced_to_jail_time-227052-1.html|title=Jesse Jackson Jr. and Wife Sentenced to Jail Time|date=August 14, 2013|publisher=Roll Call}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, in the case of ''Roman Catholic Archbishop of Washington v. Sebelius'', Jackson ruled against the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Washington]] in its challenge to the [[contraceptive mandate]] under the [[Affordable Care Act]] as applied to its employees.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/national/2013/12/23/315288.htm|title=Judge Rejects Catholic Church Challenge to Obamacare Birth Control Coverage|date=December 23, 2013|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] and other agencies made accommodations for religious organizations, under which such organizations do not have to \"provide, pay for, or facilitate access to contraception\" if they certify their objection to doing so.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\"/><ref name=\"Archdiocese\">''[http://rewire.news/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Roman-Cath.-Archb.-of-Wash.-Dist.-Ct.-Order.pdf Roman Catholic Archbishop of Washington v. Sebelius]'', 1:13-cv-01441-ABJ (December 20, 2013).</ref> Jackson rejected the archdiocese's argument that the act of \"self-certifying\" in itself constitutes a substantial burden on the archdiocese's right to freely exercise religion.<ref name=\"Archdiocese\"/>\n\nIn May 2017, Jackson dismissed a wrongful death suit filed against former [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] by the parents of two of the Americans killed in [[2012 Benghazi attack|the 2012 attack on the American diplomatic compound in Benghazi]], Libya, on the basis of the [[Westfall Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2017/05/27/Judge-dismisses-wrongful-death-suit-against-Clinton-over-Benghazi/5811495910092/?st_rec=2341495913466|title=Judge dismisses wrongful death suit against Clinton over Benghazi|date=May 27, 2017|publisher=UPI}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Jackson was assigned to preside over the criminal case that Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]] brought against [[Paul Manafort]] and [[Rick Gates (political consultant)|Rick Gates]] as part of his [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 election cycle]]. She accepted their \"not guilty\" pleas, granted bail, confiscated their passports, and ordered them to be held under house arrest. She also warned defense lawyers not to discuss the case outside of court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/11/02/561692221/manafort-and-gates-to-remain-restricted-to-their-homes-judge-says|title=Manafort And Gates To Remain Restricted To Their Homes, Judge Says|last=Lucas|first=Ryan|date=November 2, 2017|work=NPR|accessdate=November 4, 2017}}</ref> On June 15, 2018, after the prosecution accused him of attempted [[witness tampering]], Jackson revoked Manafort's bail and sent him to jail until his upcoming federal trials.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-15/manafort-sent-to-jail-after-judge-cancels-house-arrest-jig5977k|title=Manafort Heads to Jail After Judge Faults Witness Tampering|date=June 15, 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=June 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On February 23, 2018, Gates pleaded guilty to one count of [[Making false statements|false statements]] and one count of [[conspiracy against the United States]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/23/former-trump-campaign-official-rick-gates-pleads-guilty-on-two-counts.html|title=Former Trump campaign official Rick Gates pleads guilty to lying and conspiracy against the US|last=Breuninger|first=Kevin|date=February 23, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> The plea bargain included an agreement to cooperate with the Mueller investigation.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/16/us/politics/rick-gates-russia.html|title=How the Russia Investigation Entangled a Manafort Prot\u00e9g\u00e9|last=Confessore|first=Nicholas|date=June 16, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 30, 2017|last2=Meier|first2=Barry|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On September 14, 2018, Manafort pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy against the United States. The plea bargain included an agreement to cooperate with the Mueller investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/14/us/politics/manafort-plea-deal.html|title=Paul Manafort Agrees to Cooperate With Special Counsel; Pleads Guilty to Reduced Charges|last=LaFraniere|first=Sharon|date=September 14, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 15, 2018|last2=Vogel|first2=Kenneth|language=en-US}}</ref> On February 13, 2019, Jackson ruled that Manafort had lied to Mueller's office, the FBI, and a grand jury after his guilty plea about his interactions with [[Konstantin Kilimnik]], a man the FBI believes has ties to Russian intelligence agencies. Jackson ruled that the special counsel was no longer bound by the terms of Manafort's plea, which included advocating a sentence reduction for him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/us-judge-finds-paul-manafort-lied-to-mueller-probe-about-contacts-with-russian-aide/2019/02/13/c5209f7a-2f2c-11e9-86ab-5d02109aeb01_story.html |title=Federal judge finds Paul Manafort lied to Mueller probe about contacts with Russian aide |author=Spencer S. Hsu |work=The Washington Post |date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2018, Jackson sentenced [[Alex van der Zwaan]] to one month in prison, a $20,000 fine, and two months of supervised release.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/zoetillman/a-lawyer-who-admitted-lying-to-the-special-counsels-office|title=A Lawyer Who Admitted Lying To The Special Counsel's Office Was Just Sentenced To One Month In Jail|last=Tillman|first=Zoe|date=April 3, 2018|work=Buzzfeed|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019 Jackson was assigned the case of [[Roger Stone]], an informal advisor to candidate [[Donald Trump]], following his indictment by the Mueller investigation on seven counts including false statements, obstruction, and witness tampering.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-25/roger-stone-arrested-in-florida-as-part-of-special-counsel-probe|title=Trump Associate Roger Stone Arrested in Florida as Part of Special Counsel Probe|first1=Andrew M.|last1=Harris|first2=David|last2=Kocieniewski|first3=David|last3=Voreacos|website=Bloomberg|date=January 25, 2019|access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref> On February 15, 2019, Jackson imposed a limited gag order on him and his attorneys.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/15/politics/roger-stone-gag-order/index.html|title=Judge puts gag order on Roger Stone and attorneys|last=Polantz|first=Katelyn|date=February 15, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref> On February 18, he posted an [[Instagram]] of Jackson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/roger-stone-judge-instagram_n_5c6b1233e4b0b9cc78ff507e|title=Roger Stone Attacks Judge Presiding Over His Case In Bizarre Instagram Post|last=Campbell|first=Andy|date=February 18, 2019|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref> Stone took it down and apologized, but on February 21, Jackson tightened the terms of his gag order, saying, \"From this moment on, the defendant may not speak publicly about this case\u2014period.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/19/politics/roger-stone-gag-order/index.html|title=Judge calls new hearing on gag order after Roger Stone's inflammatory post|last=Polantz|first=Katelyn|date=February 19, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/roger-stone-apologizes-to-judge-for-instagram-post-my-wife-is-kicking-me|title=Judge rips into Roger Stone, bars him from speaking publicly on case: 'There will be no third chance'|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=February 21, 2019|work=Fox News|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, prosecutors recommended a seven- to nine-year federal prison sentence for Stone. President Trump called the recommendation unfair and \"a miscarriage of justice\". The [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] recommended a shorter sentence, indicating that it should be \"far less.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/doj-backpedalling-sentencing-recommendation-trump-ally-roger-stone-n1134961|title=All four Roger Stone prosecutors resign from case after DOJ backpedals on sentencing recommendation|website=NBC News}}</ref> Trump criticized Jackson via Twitter over earlier judicial rulings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/02/12/trump-stone-judge/|title=Trump attacks federal judge, prosecutors in Twitter tirade defending Roger Stone|last=Chiu|first=Allyson|date=February 12, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref> On February 20, 2020, Jackson said before Stone's sentencing: \u201cHe was not prosecuted, as some have claimed, for standing up for the president. He was prosecuted for covering up for the president.\u201d Jackson denied that Stone was being punished for his politics or his allies.<ref>[https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/made-of-steel-judge-amy-berman-jackson-set-to-sentence-roger-stone-after-trumps-attacks/2220486/ \u2018Made of Steel\u2019: Judge Amy Berman Jackson Sentences Roger Stone After Trump\u2019s Attacks], ''[[NBC]]'', Noreen O'Donnell, February 20, 2020. Retrieved February 22, 2020.]</ref> She sentenced him to 40 months in federal prison, plus a $20,000 fine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/20/roger-stone-sentencing-hearing-underway/4798388002/|title=Truth still matters': Judge sentences Roger Stone to 40 months in prison for obstructing Congress' Russia investigation|last=Wu|first=Kristine Phillips, Kevin Johnson and Nicholas|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> Stone's lawyers moved to disqualify Jackson; Jackson denied the motion on the basis of lack of \"factual or legal support\" for it.<ref>John Bowden, [https://thehill.com/regulation/484289-judge-denies-roger-stones-motion-to-disqualify-her Judge denies Roger Stone's motion to disqualify her], ''The Hill'' (February 23, 2020).</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nJackson served on the board of the Washington D.C. Rape Crisis Center and has also been a member of the Parent Steering Committee of the Interdisciplinary Council on Developmental and Learning Disorders.<ref name=\"ATTORNEYS, Amy Berman Jackson\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn her spare time, Jackson writes music and sings.<ref name=\"NYT-Profile\" />\n\nShe is married to Darryl W. Jackson, who worked in [[Export Enforcement]] as Assistant Secretary of Commerce for [[George W. Bush]] in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/results/leadership/bio_813.html |title=Darryl Jackson -- Department of Commerce |quote=On October 7, 2005, the United States Senate confirmed President Bush's nomination of Darryl W. Jackson, of the District of Columbia, to be Assistant Secretary of Commerce for Export Enforcement}}</ref> after leaving the [[Arnold & Porter]] firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldporter.com/en/perspectives/news/2005/07/darryl-jackson-nominated-by-white-house-to-expor__ |date=July 11, 2005 |title=Darryl Jackson Nominated by White House to Export Control Position}}</ref> They have two sons,<ref name=\"NYT-Profile\">{{Cite news |last=LaFraniere |first=Sharon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/amy-berman-jackson-roger-stone.html |title=Judge in Roger Stone Trial Confronts a High-Pressure Decision |date=February 20, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> one of whom is [[Matt Jackson (Jeopardy! contestant)|Matt Jackson]], who won 13 straight games on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'', earning $411,612.<ref>{{cite web|title='Jeopardy!' mastermind Matt Jackson loses in classiest way possible|url=https://mashable.com/2015/10/14/matt-jackson-loses-jeopardy/|last=Ellis|first=Johnathan|publisher=Mashable|date=October 14, 2015|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FJC Bio|nid=1393656}}\n* {{Ballotpedia|Amy_B._Jackson|Amy Berman Jackson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gladys Kessler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]}}|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{United States DC Circuit district judges}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Amy Berman}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American judges]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women judges]]\n[[Category:Assistant United States Attorneys]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:United States district court judges appointed by Barack Obama]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix          =\n| name                      = Amy Berman Jackson\n| honorific-suffix          =\n| image                     = Amy Berman Jackson.jpg\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| office                    = Judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]\n| term_start                = March 18, 2011\n| term_end                  =\n| nominator                 =\n| appointer                 = [[List of federal judges appointed by Barack Obama|Barack Obama]]\n| predecessor               = [[Gladys Kessler]]\n| successor                 =\n| pronunciation             =\n| birth_name                =Amy Berman\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1954|07|22}}\n| birth_place               = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]\n| death_date                =\n| death_place               =\n| death_cause               =\n| resting_place             =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| citizenship               =\n| nationality               =\n| party                     =\n| height                    =\n| spouse                    = Darryl Jackson<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/>\n| partner                   =\n| relations                 =\n| children                  = [[Matt Jackson (Jeopardy! contestant)|Matthew Barnett Jackson]]<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2015/10/07/washington-jeopardy-contestant-matt-jackson-is-a-pop-culture-sensation-and-the-son-of-a-federal-judge/ | title=Washington \u2018Jeopardy\u2019 contestant Matt Jackson is a pop-culture sensation&nbsp;\u2014 and the son of a federal judge | publisher=[[Washington Post]] | date=October 7, 2015 | accessdate=October 8, 2015 | author=Heil, Emily |quote=The 23 year-old contestant\u2019s father is Washington attorney Darryl Jackson, who was a Commerce Department official under former President George W. Bush.}}</ref>\n| residence                 =\n| education                 = [[Harvard College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]])<br/>[[Harvard Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])\n| alma_mater                =\n| occupation                =\n| profession                =\n| known_for                 =\n| salary                    =\n| net_worth                 =\n| cabinet                   =\n| committees                =\n| portfolio                 =\n| religion                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| website                   =\n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| footnotes                 =\n}}\n'''Amy Berman Jackson''' (born July 22, 1954) is a [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nAmy Berman was born on July 22, 1954, in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]],<ref>''Martindale-Hubbell Law Directory'', Vol. 17 ([[Martindale-Hubbell]], 2001).</ref>  She is the daughter of Mildred (Sauber) and Barnett Berman, a physician at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-2004-02-09-0402090061-story.html|title=Dr. Barnett Berman, 81, internist, Army veteran|first=Joe|last=Nawrozki|website=baltimoresun.com|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe received her [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 and her [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Harvard Law School]] in 1979.<ref name=\"fjc.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fjc.gov/history/judges/jackson-amy-berman|title=Jackson, Amy Berman|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|website=www.fjc.gov}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nAfter graduating from law school, Jackson served as a [[law clerk]] to Judge [[Harrison L. Winter]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]. From 1980 to 1986, she served as an [[United States Attorney|Assistant United States Attorney]] for the [[District of Columbia]], where she received Department of Justice Special Achievement Awards for her work on high-profile murder and sexual assault cases in 1985 and 1986. From 1986 to 1994, Jackson was an associate and then a [[Partner (business rank)|partner]] at [[Venable LLP|Venable, Baetjer, Howard and Civiletti]].<ref name=\"NamesThree\">{{cite press release |title=President Obama Names Three to United States District Court, 6/17/10 |url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/realitycheck/the-press-office/president-obama-names-three-united-states-district-court-61710|publisher=White House Office of the Press Secretary|date=June 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 until her appointment as a federal judge, Jackson was a member of the law firm Trout Cacheris & Solomon PLLC in Washington, D.C. where she specialized in complex litigation, criminal investigations and defense, criminal trials, civil trials, and appeals. In 2009 Jackson represented nine-term [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] for [[Louisiana's 2nd congressional district]] [[William J. Jefferson]] in his [[Political corruption|corruption trial]].\n\nJackson has served as an expert legal commentator for many news organizations, including [[Fox News Channel]], [[CNN]], [[NBC]], and [[MSNBC]].<ref name=\"ATTORNEYS, Amy Berman Jackson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.troutcacheris.com/attorneys-a-jackson.php |title=ATTORNEYS, Amy Berman Jackson |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |publisher=Trout Cacheris PLLC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204130857/http://www.troutcacheris.com/attorneys-a-jackson.php |archivedate=February 4, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"fjc.gov\" />\n\n==Federal judicial service==\nOn June 17, 2010, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] nominated Jackson to fill a vacant seat on the United States District Court for the District of Columbia that was created in 2007 when Judge [[Gladys Kessler]] took [[senior status]].<ref name=\"NamesThree\"/> Her nomination lapsed at the end of 2010, but Obama renominated her on January 5, 2011. The [[United States Senate]] confirmed Jackson on March 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=112&session=1&vote=00045|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 112th  Congress \u2013 1st  Session|website=www.senate.gov}}</ref> She received her commission the next day.<ref name=\"fjc.gov\"/>\n\n===Selected opinions===\nIn March 2012, Jackson ruled that the [[National Labor Relations Board]] had limited authority to require private businesses to display posters informing workers about [[labor rights]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge Clears Rule on Union Posters at Work|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/03/business/judge-clears-rule-on-union-posters-at-work.html|agency=Associated Press|date=March 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAlso in March 2012, Jackson overturned a decision by the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) that revoked a permit for the [[Spruce 1]] mine project in [[Logan County, West Virginia]], on the ground that the EPA did not have power under the [[Clean Water Act]] to rescind the permit.<ref>{{cite news|last=Broder|first=John M.|title=Court Reverses E.P.A. on Big Mining Project|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/24/science/earth/court-reverses-epa-saying-big-mining-project-can-proceed.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 24, 2012}}</ref> That ruling was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit in April 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last=Broder|first=John M.|title=Court Backs E.P.A. Veto of Mining Permit|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/24/science/earth/court-backs-epa-veto-of-mining-permit.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 24, 2013}}</ref> and on September 30, 2014, Jackson ruled in the EPA's favor, allowing its veto of the permit to stand.<ref>{{cite news|title=EPA wins another round on Spruce Mine veto|url=http://www.wvgazette.com/article/20140930/GZ01/140939918|newspaper=The Charleston Gazette|date=September 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJackson presided at the August 2013 sentencing of former U.S. Representative [[Jesse Jackson, Jr.]] and his wife, [[Sandi Jackson]] (who are not related to Judge Jackson). After guilty pleas to misuse of campaign funds, she sentenced Representative Jackson to 30 months and his wife to 12 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/jesse_jackson_jr_and_wife_sentenced_to_jail_time-227052-1.html|title=Jesse Jackson Jr. and Wife Sentenced to Jail Time|date=August 14, 2013|publisher=Roll Call}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, in the case of ''Roman Catholic Archbishop of Washington v. Sebelius'', Jackson ruled against the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Washington]] in its challenge to the [[contraceptive mandate]] under the [[Affordable Care Act]] as applied to its employees.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/national/2013/12/23/315288.htm|title=Judge Rejects Catholic Church Challenge to Obamacare Birth Control Coverage|date=December 23, 2013|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] and other agencies made accommodations for religious organizations, under which such organizations do not have to \"provide, pay for, or facilitate access to contraception\" if they certify their objection to doing so.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\"/><ref name=\"Archdiocese\">''[http://rewire.news/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Roman-Cath.-Archb.-of-Wash.-Dist.-Ct.-Order.pdf Roman Catholic Archbishop of Washington v. Sebelius]'', 1:13-cv-01441-ABJ (December 20, 2013).</ref> Jackson rejected the archdiocese's argument that the act of \"self-certifying\" in itself constitutes a substantial burden on the archdiocese's right to freely exercise religion.<ref name=\"Archdiocese\"/>\n\nIn May 2017, Jackson dismissed a wrongful death suit filed against former [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] by the parents of two of the Americans killed in [[2012 Benghazi attack|the 2012 attack on the American diplomatic compound in Benghazi]], Libya, on the basis of the [[Westfall Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2017/05/27/Judge-dismisses-wrongful-death-suit-against-Clinton-over-Benghazi/5811495910092/?st_rec=2341495913466|title=Judge dismisses wrongful death suit against Clinton over Benghazi|date=May 27, 2017|publisher=UPI}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Jackson was assigned to preside over the criminal case that Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]] brought against [[Paul Manafort]] and [[Rick Gates (political consultant)|Rick Gates]] as part of his [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 election cycle]]. She accepted their \"not guilty\" pleas, granted bail, confiscated their passports, and ordered them to be held under house arrest. She also warned defense lawyers not to discuss the case outside of court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/11/02/561692221/manafort-and-gates-to-remain-restricted-to-their-homes-judge-says|title=Manafort And Gates To Remain Restricted To Their Homes, Judge Says|last=Lucas|first=Ryan|date=November 2, 2017|work=NPR|accessdate=November 4, 2017}}</ref> On June 15, 2018, after the prosecution accused him of attempted [[witness tampering]], Jackson revoked Manafort's bail and sent him to jail until his upcoming federal trials.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-15/manafort-sent-to-jail-after-judge-cancels-house-arrest-jig5977k|title=Manafort Heads to Jail After Judge Faults Witness Tampering|date=June 15, 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=June 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On February 23, 2018, Gates pleaded guilty to one count of [[Making false statements|false statements]] and one count of [[conspiracy against the United States]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/23/former-trump-campaign-official-rick-gates-pleads-guilty-on-two-counts.html|title=Former Trump campaign official Rick Gates pleads guilty to lying and conspiracy against the US|last=Breuninger|first=Kevin|date=February 23, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> The plea bargain included an agreement to cooperate with the Mueller investigation.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/16/us/politics/rick-gates-russia.html|title=How the Russia Investigation Entangled a Manafort Prot\u00e9g\u00e9|last=Confessore|first=Nicholas|date=June 16, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 30, 2017|last2=Meier|first2=Barry|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On September 14, 2018, Manafort pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy against the United States. The plea bargain included an agreement to cooperate with the Mueller investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/14/us/politics/manafort-plea-deal.html|title=Paul Manafort Agrees to Cooperate With Special Counsel; Pleads Guilty to Reduced Charges|last=LaFraniere|first=Sharon|date=September 14, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 15, 2018|last2=Vogel|first2=Kenneth|language=en-US}}</ref> On February 13, 2019, Jackson ruled that Manafort had lied to Mueller's office, the FBI, and a grand jury after his guilty plea about his interactions with [[Konstantin Kilimnik]], a man the FBI believes has ties to Russian intelligence agencies. Jackson ruled that the special counsel was no longer bound by the terms of Manafort's plea, which included advocating a sentence reduction for him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/legal-issues/us-judge-finds-paul-manafort-lied-to-mueller-probe-about-contacts-with-russian-aide/2019/02/13/c5209f7a-2f2c-11e9-86ab-5d02109aeb01_story.html |title=Federal judge finds Paul Manafort lied to Mueller probe about contacts with Russian aide |author=Spencer S. Hsu |work=The Washington Post |date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2018, Jackson sentenced [[Alex van der Zwaan]] to one month in prison, a $20,000 fine, and two months of supervised release.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/zoetillman/a-lawyer-who-admitted-lying-to-the-special-counsels-office|title=A Lawyer Who Admitted Lying To The Special Counsel's Office Was Just Sentenced To One Month In Jail|last=Tillman|first=Zoe|date=April 3, 2018|work=Buzzfeed|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019 Jackson was assigned the case of [[Roger Stone]], an informal advisor to candidate [[Donald Trump]], following his indictment by the Mueller investigation on seven counts including false statements, obstruction, and witness tampering.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-25/roger-stone-arrested-in-florida-as-part-of-special-counsel-probe|title=Trump Associate Roger Stone Arrested in Florida as Part of Special Counsel Probe|first1=Andrew M.|last1=Harris|first2=David|last2=Kocieniewski|first3=David|last3=Voreacos|website=Bloomberg|date=January 25, 2019|access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref> On February 15, 2019, Jackson imposed a limited gag order on him and his attorneys.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/15/politics/roger-stone-gag-order/index.html|title=Judge puts gag order on Roger Stone and attorneys|last=Polantz|first=Katelyn|date=February 15, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref> On February 18, he posted an [[Instagram]] of Jackson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/roger-stone-judge-instagram_n_5c6b1233e4b0b9cc78ff507e|title=Roger Stone Attacks Judge Presiding Over His Case In Bizarre Instagram Post|last=Campbell|first=Andy|date=February 18, 2019|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref> Stone took it down and apologized, but on February 21, Jackson tightened the terms of his gag order, saying, \"From this moment on, the defendant may not speak publicly about this case\u2014period.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/19/politics/roger-stone-gag-order/index.html|title=Judge calls new hearing on gag order after Roger Stone's inflammatory post|last=Polantz|first=Katelyn|date=February 19, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/roger-stone-apologizes-to-judge-for-instagram-post-my-wife-is-kicking-me|title=Judge rips into Roger Stone, bars him from speaking publicly on case: 'There will be no third chance'|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=February 21, 2019|work=Fox News|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, prosecutors recommended a seven- to nine-year federal prison sentence for Stone. President Trump called the recommendation unfair and \"a miscarriage of justice\". The [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] recommended a shorter sentence, indicating that it should be \"far less.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/doj-backpedalling-sentencing-recommendation-trump-ally-roger-stone-n1134961|title=All four Roger Stone prosecutors resign from case after DOJ backpedals on sentencing recommendation|website=NBC News}}</ref> Trump criticized Jackson via Twitter over earlier judicial rulings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/02/12/trump-stone-judge/|title=Trump attacks federal judge, prosecutors in Twitter tirade defending Roger Stone|last=Chiu|first=Allyson|date=February 12, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref> On February 20, 2020, Jackson said before Stone's sentencing: \u201cHe was not prosecuted, as some have claimed, for standing up for the president. He was prosecuted for covering up for the president.\u201d Jackson denied that Stone was being punished for his politics or his allies.<ref>[https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/made-of-steel-judge-amy-berman-jackson-set-to-sentence-roger-stone-after-trumps-attacks/2220486/ \u2018Made of Steel\u2019: Judge Amy Berman Jackson Sentences Roger Stone After Trump\u2019s Attacks], ''[[NBC]]'', Noreen O'Donnell, February 20, 2020. Retrieved February 22, 2020.]</ref> She sentenced him to 40 months in federal prison, plus a $20,000 fine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/20/roger-stone-sentencing-hearing-underway/4798388002/|title=Truth still matters': Judge sentences Roger Stone to 40 months in prison for obstructing Congress' Russia investigation|last=Wu|first=Kristine Phillips, Kevin Johnson and Nicholas|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> Stone's lawyers moved to disqualify Jackson; Jackson denied the motion on the basis of lack of \"factual or legal support\" for it.<ref>John Bowden, [https://thehill.com/regulation/484289-judge-denies-roger-stones-motion-to-disqualify-her Judge denies Roger Stone's motion to disqualify her], ''The Hill'' (February 23, 2020).</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nJackson served on the board of the Washington D.C. Rape Crisis Center and has also been a member of the Parent Steering Committee of the Interdisciplinary Council on Developmental and Learning Disorders.<ref name=\"ATTORNEYS, Amy Berman Jackson\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn her spare time, Jackson writes music and sings.<ref name=\"NYT-Profile\" />\n\nShe is married to Darryl W. Jackson, who worked in [[Export Enforcement]] as Assistant Secretary of Commerce for [[George W. Bush]] in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/results/leadership/bio_813.html |title=Darryl Jackson -- Department of Commerce |quote=On October 7, 2005, the United States Senate confirmed President Bush's nomination of Darryl W. Jackson, of the District of Columbia, to be Assistant Secretary of Commerce for Export Enforcement}}</ref> after leaving the [[Arnold & Porter]] firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldporter.com/en/perspectives/news/2005/07/darryl-jackson-nominated-by-white-house-to-expor__ |date=July 11, 2005 |title=Darryl Jackson Nominated by White House to Export Control Position}}</ref> They have two sons,<ref name=\"NYT-Profile\">{{Cite news |last=LaFraniere |first=Sharon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/amy-berman-jackson-roger-stone.html |title=Judge in Roger Stone Trial Confronts a High-Pressure Decision |date=February 20, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> one of whom is [[Matt Jackson (Jeopardy! contestant)|Matt Jackson]], who won 13 straight games on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'', earning $411,612.<ref>{{cite web|title='Jeopardy!' mastermind Matt Jackson loses in classiest way possible|url=https://mashable.com/2015/10/14/matt-jackson-loses-jeopardy/|last=Ellis|first=Johnathan|publisher=Mashable|date=October 14, 2015|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FJC Bio|nid=1393656}}\n* {{Ballotpedia|Amy_B._Jackson|Amy Berman Jackson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gladys Kessler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]}}|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{United States DC Circuit district judges}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Amy Berman}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American judges]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women judges]]\n[[Category:Assistant United States Attorneys]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Baltimore]]